lexUnit.name: jab.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: poke roughly or quickly with something sharp or pointed.

sentence.text: A finger jabbed her between the shoulder blades .
Thrusting his big red face forward he jabbed Luke in the chest with a thick forefinger .
` Where is it ? " he asked , jabbing her again .
Covering the sprawled guards constantly , Mortimer hopped over the bodies and continued downwards , his men jabbing the bodies with bayonets to make sure .
In a mad impulsive movement , which Molly later insisted was self defence , she jabbed desperately at the oncoming fish .
How dare you speak to your mother like that ? " she jabbed repeatedly until the sight of blood seeping through Constance 's blouse stopped her short .
She relaxed slightly and jabbed him in his ribs .
A JILTED lover who took revenge on women by jabbing them in the rear with knitting needles has come unstuck .
Or if the horse has been jabbed in the mouth when it is being mounted , it goes on expecting pain in the mouth whenever it is mounted .
Take it step by step , but do not jab her in the mouth and be FAIR but FIRM .
Reatus also allegedly jabbed Mr Mounsa in the neck and hit him with a dog chain .
` Get on ! " said Teng , drawing the long club from his belt and jabbing the man viciously in the small of the back .
Ryker said , jabbing her in the ribs with his elbow .
He saw the horse rise in the same fraction of a second as the recoil jabbed his cheek .
His lance jabbed me as he passed .
In the operating theatre , a tall and ancient nurse jabs me twice to find the vein in the back of my hand .
Leonard Perkes , 80 , was beaten , jabbed with a screwdriver and had his toes cut with a knife .
